(Non-constitutional Bodies
Part 7, Lokpal and
Lokayukta)
By – Dr. Vipan Goyal

Lokpal and Lokayuktas
• ‘The success of democracy and the realisation of socio-economic
development depends on the extent to which the citizens’
grievances are redressed.’
• The institution of Ombudsman was first created in Sweden in 1809.
• ‘Ombud’ is a Swedish term and refers to a person who acts as the
representative or spokesman of another person.
• According to Donald C. Rowat, Ombudsman refers to “an officer
appointed by the legislature to handle complaints against
administrative and judicial action.”
• Spread to other Scandinavian countries.
• The United Kingdom adopted Ombudsman-like institution called Parliamentary
Commissioner for Administration in 1967. (New Zealand in 1962)
LOKPAL
• The 1st Administrative Reforms Commission (ARC) of India (1966–1970) recommended the
setting up of two special authorities designated as ‘Lokpal’ and ‘Lokayuktas’.
 Lokpal - complaints against ministers and secretaries at Central and state levels
 Lokayuktas - complaints against other specified higher officials.
**The ARC kept the judiciary outside the purview of Lokpal and Lokayuktas as in New Zealand.
But, in Sweden the judiciary is within the purview of Ombudsman.
• 10 official attempts have been made to bring about legislation on this subject
by tabling bills in Parliament
• Finally, the LOKPAL AND LOKAYUKTAS ACT (2013) was passed in December
2013 and effective from January 2014
2011 – Anna hazare led
 Lokpal movement
The salient features of the Lokpal and Lokayuktas Act (2013)
1. Lokpal at the Centre
 Lokayukta at the State level

The jurisdiction of Lokpal includes the Prime Minister, Ministers, Members of
Parliament and Groups A, B, C and D officers and officials of the Central
Government.
2. The Lokpal to consist of a Chairperson with a maximum of 8 members of which
50% shall be judicial members.
3. 50% of the members of the Lokpal shall come from amongst the SCs, the STs,
the OBCs, minorities and women.
4. Selection Committee -
Prime Minister
Speaker of the Lok Sabha
Leader of the Opposition in the Lok Sabha
CJI or a sitting SC Judge nominated by him (CJI)
An eminent jurist - to be nominated by President on the basis of
recommendations of the first 4 members of the selection committee
The following persons cannot become chairperson of Lokpal:
• MPs and MLAs
• Persons convicted of any offense involving moral turpitude
• Less than 45 years of age
• Members of Panchayats or Municipality
• A person who was removed or dismissed from the public service
• A person who holds any office of trust / profit; if so, he would need to
resign from Lok Sabha
• A person who is affiliated to a political party
• Carries on some business / profession; if so, he would need to quit some
business
• The term of office for Lokpal Chairman and Members is 5 years or till
attaining age of 70 years.
• The salary, allowances and other conditions of service of
chairperson are equivalent to Chief Justice of India and members is
equivalent to Judge of Supreme Court.
LOKAYUKTAS
• Even much before the enactment of the Lokpal and Lokayuktas Act (2013)
itself, many states had already set up the institution of Lokayuktas.
First Lokayukta was created in Maharashtra*
• Appointed by the governor of the state.
• While appointing, the governor in most of the states consults (a) the chief
justice of the state high court, and (b) the leader of Opposition in the state
legislative assembly
• In most of the states, the term of office fixed for Lokayukta is of 5 years
duration or 65 years of age,
1. The Lokayukta presents, annually, to the governor of the state a
consolidated report on his performance. The governor places this report
along with an explanatory memorandum before the state legislature.
The Lokayukta is responsible to the state legislature.
2. He takes the help of the state investigating agencies for conducting
inquiries.
3. He can call for relevant files and documents from the state government
departments.
4. The recommendations made by the Lokayukta are only advisory and not
binding on the state government.

