ACIDS, BASES AND
METALLOIDS
By Dr Vipan Goyal

Acid and Base
• ACID
 An acid is a substance that releases hydrogen ions (H+)in
aqueous solutions.
 Ex:- Hydrochloric acid (HCL) ,Acetic acid (CH3COOH).
• BASE
 A substance that releases hydroxide ions (OH¯) in aqueous
solutions.
 Ex:- Sodium hydroxide (NaOH), NH4OH.
ACIDS ON BASES ON PH SCALE
• PH scale – The negative logarithm of H+ ions is called PH scale. It ranges
from negative to 14th value.
• STRONG / WEAK ACID: The acids having ph ranges less than 2 are
considered as strong acid and more than 2 are considered as weak acid or
the acidity decreases from left to right in a PH scale. Ex- CH3COOH is a
weak acid while HCl is a strong base.
• STRONG BASE / WEAK BASE: The base which have ph range 7 to 14 are
considered as base. The basicity increases from 7 to 14. The strongest
bases has the ph of 14. Ex- NH4OH is a weak base while NaOH is a strong
base.

• Acids
• These are the substance, which have sour taste and turn blue litmus red.
• These are good conductor of electricity in aqueous solution.
• Pickels are always kept in glass jar because acid present in them reacts with metal
to produce hydrogen gas.
• Bases
• These are the substances, which have bitter taste and turn red litmus, blue.
• They give different colours in acid and base solutions.
• Salts
• These are the product of neutralisation reaction between an acid and a base.
• pH is the measure of acidity/basicity.
BUFFER SOLUTION
• A solution whose ph does not change when small amount of an
acid or a base is added to it.
• Example: Blood contains a buffer of carbonic acid (H 2CO 3) and
bicarbonate anion (HCO 3 -) in order to maintain blood pH between
7.35 and 7.45, as a value higher than 7.8 or lower than 6.8 can lead
to death.
• In this buffer, hydronium H3O+ and bicarbonate anion HCO3
- are in
equilibrium with carbonic acid.
INDICATORS
INDICATORS
• Litmus is a water-soluble mixture of different dyes extracted from lichens.
• It is often adsorbed onto filter paper to produce one of the oldest forms of
pH indicator, used to test materials for acidity.
• Adsorption is the adhesion of atoms, ions or molecules from a gas, liquid
or dissolved solid to a surface. This process creates a film of the adsorbate
on the surface of the adsorbent.
• Phenolphthalein is basically used in acid base titrations (also used for
alcohol check while driving.)

• HCL – Hydrochloric Acid
• Vitamin C – Ascorbic Acid
• Uric Acid – Urine Of Birds
• Lactic Acid – Urine Of Birds
• Lactic Acid – Muscles (During Anaerobic Respiration)
• Butyric acid- Rancid butter
• Tarteric acid – Grapes
• Carbonic Acid- Sodawater
• Amino Acid – Proteins
• Oxalic acid is used to remove rust spots.
• HCl is used as bathroom cleaner.
 AQUA-REGIA: It contains the mixture of acids and bases in the ratio of 3:1. (HCl : HNO3)
Usually used by goldsmiths to dissolve gold.
Uses of some bases
• Aluminium hydroxide : used to make gastric medicine (antacid)
• Calcium hydroxide : used in sewage treatment
• Sodium hydroxide : used in manufacturing of Soaps, detergents and
cleaners.
• Magnesium hydroxide : used as an antacid, used as antiperspirant
armpit deodorant
• Ammonia : Production of fertilisers, in nitric acid manufacturing,
neutralise acid in petroleum industry and prevent premature
coagulation in natural/synthetic latex.
• Latex is used in mattresses, gloves, swim caps, catheters and
ballons etc.
Important facts of acids and bases
• Ant or bee contains methanoic or formic acid, due to which
victim feel pain and irritation. Use of mild base like baking
soda is a remedy of it.
• Excessive use of fertilisers makes the soil more acidic. To
neutralise it, quicklime is added to soil as acidic soil is not
good for the growth of plant.
• Pickles are always kept in glass jar because acid present in
them reacts with the metal of metallic pot.
Importance of pH in Everyday Life
• The pH value of a human body ranges between 7.0 and 7.8.
• The stomach of a human body produces hydrochloric acid that helps in the
digestion of food; surprisingly, it does not harm the stomach anyway.
However, when the stomach produces too much acid (known as
indigestion), it causes pain and irritation.
• To get relief from this pain, doctors suggest the use of bases known as
antacids. These antacids neutralize and control the increased amount of
acid.
• The teeth, which are made up of calcium phosphate, is the hardest
substance in the body.
Importance of pH in Everyday Life
• However, when the pH in the mouth decreases (below 5.5), it corrodes the
teeth.
• The salt, normally, is formed by the combination of hydrochloric acid and
sodium hydroxide solution; and, the combination is known as sodium
chloride.
• When the pH value of rain water is measured as less than 5.6, it is known
as acid rain.
• When acid rain flows into the rivers, then it also lowers the pH of the river
water
• The acidic river water is threat for the survival of aquatic life.
pH of some important substances
