Tuglaq Dynasty
By Dr Vipan Goyal

Introduction
• After killing Mubarak Shah, Khusru Khan mounted the throne as Sultan
Nasiruddin.
• He ordered mass killing in the Harem of the Sultan and everybody alive was killed.
• Khusru, a Hindu convert, took the revenge of his forceful covert by eliminating the
whole of the Khalji dynasty and this was the end of another dynasty of the Delhi
Sultanate in 1320 AD.
• The Muslims were in abject fear of this Hindu convert followed by a Hindu uprising
in Delhi and all their hopes were now on Ghazi Malik.
Introduction
• The Tughlaqs were a Muslim family of Turkic origin. The dynasty reached its zenith
point between AD 1330 and 1335 when Muhammad Bin Tughlaq led military
campaign.
• Its rule was marked by torture, cruelty and rebellions, resulting in the rapid
disintegration of the dynasty's territorial reach after 1335 AD.
• This dynasty is also known as Qaraunah Turks as the father of Ghiasuddin Tuglaq
was a Qaraunah Turk.
Tuglaq Dynasty
Ghiyas-ud-din Tughluq or Ghazi Malik
(1320 – 1325 A.D.)
• Ghiyas-ud-din Tughluq or Ghazi Malik was the founder of the Tughluq
dynasty.
• His father was a Turk and mother was a Jat woman of Punjab.
• Ghazi Malik was a general of Alauddin Khalji.
• He was the first sultan who took the title of Ghazi or slayer of infidels.
• Ghazi means 'to carry out a military expedition.
• Slayer of infidels means someone who kills a person who does not follow
the same religion you do.
Ghiyas-ud-din Tughluq or Ghazi Malik
(1320 – 1325 A.D.)
• He strengthened the defence of the North-Western
frontier in order to check the Mongol invasions.
and secured Multan, Sindh and Uch for his master.
• His son Fakhr-ud-din Muhammad Jauna Khan defeated
the Kakatiya ruler of Warangal, Prataparudra-Deva II.
• His son Fakhr Malik who later became Muhammad Bin
Tuglaq was in Delhi and was aware of the critical state of
affairs in Delhi.
• He went to Multan secretly and told his father what was
happening in Delhi.
• The father son duo, i.e. Ghazi Malik and Fakhr Malik, both
great warriors, marched towards Delhi to save Delhi from
this Hindu convert devourer.
Ghiyas-ud-din Tughluq or Ghazi Malik
(1320 – 1325 A.D.)
• Fearful Khusru Khan (the last king of the Khilji dynasty) with all the troops he
could gather, emptied the treasury and scattered the hoard in among the soldiers.
• The Muslim soldiers took the money but did not take up arms against Ghazi Malik.
• Khusru, with his limited number of Hindu men and a few rebel Muslims tried to
withstand Ghazi Malik, the champion of the Alauddin’s faith.
• The reign of terror ended, and India passed in the hands of another foreign
dynasty.
• Ghazi Malik founded the city of Tughlaqabad.
Ghiyas-ud-din Tughluq or Ghazi Malik
(1320 – 1325 A.D.)
• He put down the revolt of Ghiyasuddin Bahadur in Bengal.
• On returning from Bengal, he died in 1325, from the collapse of a wooden
pavilion.
• According to the some historians, he died because of the conspiracy
hatched by his son Jauna Khan because the pavilion was constructed by
the royal architect (Mir Imard) Ahmad.
• Ibn Batuta, the Moroccon traveller, who was in Delhi at that time, opined
that his death was due to sabotage arranged by his son, Jauna Khan.
Domestic and Foreign Policies
• Ghiyas-ud-din reinstated order in his empire.
• He gave more importance to postal arrangements, judicial, irrigation,
agriculture, and police.
• In 1320A.D. he ascended the throne
• He brought Bengal, Utkala or Orissa, and Warangal under his control
• The Mongol leaders who invaded North India were seized and confined by
him.
Domestic and Foreign Policies
• Ghiyas ud-Din Tughluq reintroduced the food market laws which were
earlier implemented by his master.
• He liberalized Alauddin’s administrative policies and took keen interest in
the construction of canals (first sultan to do so).
• He tried to revive all the reforms which were necessary and were earlier
implemented.
• Ghiyas ud-Din Tughluq successfully attempted to bring the peace and
prosperity.
Domestic and Foreign Policies
• Under his elder son Fakhr Malik or Jauna or Ulugh Khan, Deccan
Provinces were recovered.
• He re-establish the authority of warangal (Kakatiyas) and Madurai
(Pandyas).
• He had a troublesome relationship with Shaikh Nizamuddin Aulia.
Muhammad-bin-Tughlaq (1325-1361 A.D.)
• In 1325 A.D. Jauna khan, the crown prince
sworn the title Muhammad-bin-Tughluq.
• Muhammad-bin-Tughlaq stood for the
administrative and political unity of India.
• In 1327 A.D. he captured Warangal.
• Jauna Khan succeeded his father in AD
1325 under the title of Muhammad- binTughlaq.
Muhammad-bin-Tughlaq
(1325-1361 A.D.)
• He was the most learned scholars of his time.
• He knew both Arabic and Persian and had comprehensive knowledge of
philosophy, astronomy, logic, mathematics and physical science.
• Toghan Timur (AD 1341), who came to seek permission to rebuild
Buddhist Monasteries, in the Himalayan region which were destroyed
during the crucial expedition.
• The sultan gave the permission and sent Ibn Batuta to the court of the
Chinese emperor in 1347.
Muhammad-bin-Tughlaq
(1325-1361 A.D.)
• Ibn Batutah was a traveller from Morocco.
• He came to India in 1333 and was appointed as the chief Qazi of Delhi for
8 years by Muhammad-bin-Tughlaq and recorded the contemporary
Indian scene in his Safarnamah (called Rehla) in Arabic language.
• Muhammad-bin-Tughlaq is also known as wisest fool because of five
reasons.
• To fill the empty treasury, he raised taxes in the Doab region.
1. Taxes in the Doab region
• Instead of actual produce standard yield was taken into account based on
the officially assumed prices.
• Unfortunately, the rain failed and there was a terrible famine in the
country. The taxes were collected rigorously. The peasants revolted in the
doab. Later, several measures were taken by the Sultan.
• He created an agricultural department, "Diwan-i-Kohi" under the charge of
"Diwan-i-Amir-i-Koht" to bring barren land under cultivation.
• Sondhar (agricultural) loans were advanced to dig wells and to buy seed
and implements.
• Shiqdars were appointed and given large sums of money to implement the
scheme, but they were incompetent and the scheme failed.
• However, the scheme became a part of the agricultural policy of the
Mughals.
• Many people ran away to the forests to avoid heavy taxes due to which
cultivation was neglected and severe food shortage occurred.
2. Transfer of Capital (1327)
• It appears that the Sultan wanted to make Devagiri second capital so that
he might be able to control south India better.
• Devagiri was named as Daulatabad present in MHA aurangabad districts.
• However, after a couple of years, Muhammad Tughlaq decided to abandon
Daulatabad largely because he soon found that just as he could not control
south India from Delhi, he could not control North from Daulatabad.
3. Introduction of Token
Currency (1330)
• Muhammad Tughlaq decided to introduce
bronze coins, which were to have the
same value as the silver coins.
• Muhammad Tughlaq might have been
successful if he could prevent people
from forging the new coins.
• He was not able to to do so and so on the
new coins began to be greatly devalued in
markets.
• One of the most unique reforms of the sultan is said to be inspired by the
introduction of paper token currency in China and Iran.
• In his first reform, he replaced the old gold and silver coins weighing 175 grains by
new coins
 Dinar gold coins - 200 grains
 Adali silver coins - 140 grains
• Then he ordered the Tanka to be minted in bronze instead of silver and fixed the
value of the new bronze coins at par with the silver tanka.
• The value of coins dropped; hence he had to withdraw the token currency.
• To conquer Khurasan, Iraq, and Transoxiana, he raised an
army of 3,70,000 men.
• But the scheme was abandoned as conditions in Iraq
improved.
4. Khurasan Expedition
• The plan for the conquest of Karajal (Kumaon hills) also met with a
disastrous end.
• Mohammed-bin-Tughluq’s national treasure had a great burden due to the
policy of huge presents given to Tamashirin, the Mongol leader in order to
avoid Mongol Invasion.
• Mohammed-bin-Tughluq’s domestic policies were good but due to faulty
implementation measures, they failed.
5. Conquest of Karajal
(Kumaon hills)
• The decline of the Delhi Sultanate is claimed due to his hasty decisions
and defective policy implementation.
• During the last days, the whole of the South India became independent
and three major states Empire of Vijayanagara, The Bahamani kingdom
and Sultnate of Madura was founded.
• He built the fortress of Adilabad and city of Jahanpanah.
Muhammad-bin-Tughlaq (1325-1361 A.D.)
Reforms and Experiments
• Sultan lacked political judgement and common sense and, rather obsesses
with his theoretical knowledge, indulged in lofty theories and visionary
projects, which failed.
• Delhi Sultanate has reached its zenith during the reign of Mohd. Bin
Tuglaq. His empire was divided into 23 provinces.
Firoz Tughlaq
(1351-1 388 A.D.)
• In 1351A.D. Firoz Tughlaq was the son of Ghiyas-ud-din Tughlaq’s younger
brother. He succeeded the throne.
• He was not a distinguished military leader his campaigns are as follows:
• He led two unsuccessful campaigns into Bengal against Haji Iliyas (Shams-uddin Iliyas Shah) and Sikandar Shah.
• Tartar Khan commanded the army.
• The Rai of Jajnagar (modern Orissa) and Nagarkot and the ruler of Sind (Jam
Babaniya) surrendered before the sultan.
• He also indirectly acknowledged the independence of the Balmani king by
receiving embassy from him.
Administrative Reforms
• He withdrew all Taquavi (agricultural) loans granted by Mohammed-binTughlaq.
• He raised the salary of the revenue officers.
• He brought to an end to all unlawful and unjust taxes.
• He took steps to translate Hindu religious texts and Sanskrit books on
music into Persian.
Administrative Reforms
• He collected four important taxes which are:
 Kharaj- 1/10 of the produce of the land
 Khams- 1/5 of the war booty
 Jizya-Poll Tax/ Tax by non muslims even by Brahmins.
 Zakat-Tax on Muslims for specific religious purposes. (2.5%)
Administrative Reforms
• He constructed 150 wells, 100 bridges, and 50 dams, and also dug many
irrigation canals.
• Construction of canals for irrigation from
 Yamuna to the city of Hissar
 From the Sutlej to the Ghaggar
 From the Ghaggar to Firuzabad
 From Mandvi and Sirmour Hills to Hansi in Haryana.
Administrative Reforms
• He constructed towns like Firozabad, Hissar, Jaunpur, and Fatehabad.
• Built his capital Firozabad ( the present day Feroz Shah Kotla in Delhi) and
to beautify it, brought 2 Ashokan pillars, one from Topra in Ambala and
other from Meerut.
• He rebuilt two storeys of QutubMinar which were damaged by lightening
in 1368 AD.
• Firoz banned all kinds of damages and torture.
Administrative Reforms
• He carried out many reforms and works of public utility with the help of
his able minister - Khan-i-Jehan Maqbool, a Hindu convert.
• He revived the Jagir system (grant of lands) which had been abolished by
Alauddin and granted it to his military officials in lieu of cash salaries.
• The iqtas granted and the post of officials and soldiers was made
hereditary not only in civil offences but also in army.
• This reduced the competent men and has negative impact on the army.
Administrative Reforms
• He organized the institution of slavery into a system and employed them
in Royal Karkhanas and other production activities.
• A separate department, Diwan-i- Bandagan, was established for the
welfare of the people.
• He established a charity bureau called Diwan-i-Khairat for the help of poor
persons, widows and or phans and through which pecuniary help was
distributed for the marriage of poor Muslim girls.
• A charitable hospital called Darul-Shafa was set up at Delhi was free
medicine and diet was supplied.
Administrative Reforms
• He also established Diwan-i-lstibqaq to give financial aid to the poor.
• Foreign Policy
 Firoz Tughlaq surrounded Bengal in 1353 A.D. and 1359 A.D.
 He seized Jainagar.
 He devastated the Jagannath Temple at Puri.
• Firoz proved his prominence by
 His generous measures and contributions to the affluence of the people.
 Futuhat-i-Firoz Shahi is an autobiography of Firoz Tughlaq.
 He patronized scholar Zia-ud-din Barani and wrote Tarikh-i-Ferozshahi and
Fatwa-i-Jahandari.
 During his reign, a number of Sanskrit books on medicine, science and arts were
translated into Persian.
 Khwaja Abdul Malik Isami wrote Futuh-us-Sulatin.
 Kutab- Feroz Shahi – a book which dealt with Physics
 He also introduced two new coins- Adha (50% jital) and bikh (25% jital)
 Also issued Shashgani, a silver coin.
Later Tughlaqs
• Successors of Firoz
 Ghiyas-ud-din Tughlaq Shah II
 Abu Bakr Shah,
 Nasir-ud-din Mohammed Tughlaq
End of Tughlug Dynasty
• The successors of Firoz were not very strong or competent.
• By the end of the 14th century, most of the territories became
independent.
• The Malwa, Gujarat and Sharqi (Jaunpur) Kingdoms broke away from the
Sultanate.
• Only Punjab and Delhi remained under the Tughlaqs.
• Timur’s invasion took place during the Tughlug period
Timur’s Invasion (1398 A.D.)
• The fabulous wealth of India attracted Timur the ruler of Samarqand.
• During the period of Nasir-ud-din Mohammed Tughlaq, he invaded India.
• In 1398 A.D. Timur captured Delhi and caused the annihilation of the
Tughlaq dynasty by pillaging and slaughtering people.

