Human Blood
By Dr Vipan Goyal

Human Blood
• Blood is a fluid connective tissue
• Blood is a part of extracellular (blood flows outside the cells) fluid
within the cardiovascular system. The role of blood in internal
environmental = Homeostatis (blood balances the body)
Functions
1. Transport oxygen, harmones and energy.
2. pH buffer – BLOOD pH value is around 7.4(using bicarbonate ions)
3. temperature or thermal maintenance – 98.4° F
4. Immunity and defense
Blood Composition
• Blood is composed of: Plasma (55%) + blood cells (44%) + white
blood cells and platelets (1%)
• 5-6 litres of blood in a body.
• Blood components
 Plasma: corpuscles
 Liquid part: RBC, WBC, Platlets
 Platelets (250 – 400 thousand),
 Erythrocytes (4.2 – 5.8 million,
 Leukocytes (5-9 thousand)
Blood
• Hematocrit: The percentage of total blood volume that blood cells
occupy.
• The normal value of plasma in
 Male is 40-50%,
 Female is 37-48%
 New born is 55%.
Plasma
• Plasma is a straw coloured, (pale yellow) viscous fluid constituting
nearly 55 per cent of the blood.
• 90-92 per cent of plasma is water and proteins contribute 6-8 per
cent of it.
• Fibrinogen, globulins and albumins are the major proteins.
• Fibrinogens are needed for clotting or coagulation of blood.
• Globulins primarily are involved in defense mechanisms of the body
• Albumins help in osmotic balance.
• Most of albumin and globulin, made from liver.
Plasma
• Plasma also contains small amounts of minerals like Na+, Ca++, Mg++,
HCO3-, Cl-, etc. Glucose, amino acids, lipids, etc., are also present in the
plasma as they are always in transit in the body.
• Factors for coagulation or clotting of blood are also present in the plasma
in an inactive form.
• Plasma without the clotting factors/Fibrinogen is called serum.
• Function of plasma protein:
 Transportation, Forms colloid osmotic pressure (albumin), Coagulation
and anticoagulation.
 Provides buffer action. Globulin protein provides immunity.
Blood Cells
• The forming processes of erythrocytes (red blood cell, RBC),
leukocytes (white blood cell, WBC) and thrombocytes (platelets)
originating from hematopoietic stem cells.
• Hematopoietic stem cells are found in the peripheral blood and the
bone marrow, are called hemopoiesis.
• During young age, yellow marrow makes RBC. During adulthood
(after 18), red marrow makes RBCs.
Red Blood Cells (RBC)
• Erythrocytes or red blood cells (RBC) are
the most abundant of all the cells in blood.
• A healthy adult man has, on an average, 5
million to 5.5 million of RBCs mm3 of
blood.
• Normal value about RBC
 Male adult, 5.0×1012/L
 Female adult, 4.2×1012/L
 Newborn, ≥ 6.0×1012/L
Red Blood Cells (RBC)
• RBCs are formed in the red bone marrow in the adults and In Liver
in children.
• RBCs are devoid of nucleus/ Enucleated. (DNA absent) Exception
camel and lama
• Biconcave in shape.
• RBCs have an average life span of 120 days
• Destroyed in the spleen and liver (graveyard of RBCs).
• Spleen acts as blood bank in case of haemorrhagic shock.
Red Blood Cells (RBC)
