haemoglobin, hence the colour and name of these cells. (12-16 gm)
• Protein within RBC is hemoglobin (Hb).
 Hb in male adult, 120~160 g/L;
 Hb in female adult, 110~150 g/L;
 Hb in newborn (within 5 days), ≥ 200 g/L
• Haem – Iron/ Ferric form – Red in colour
• Globin – Protein – combine O2 and CO2
• Iron compound- Hematin
Red Blood Cells (RBC)
• CO has 200 times capacity to bind with Hb as compared to O2
Red Blood Cells (RBC)
