Lymphocytes
• T-lymphocytes involved in
cellular immunity.
• Cellular immunity is a protective
immune process that involves
the activation of phagocytes,
antigen-sensitized cytotoxic T
cells and the release of cytokines
and chemokines in response to
antigen.
Lymphocytes
• B-Lymphocytes involved in humoral immunity – produce
antibodies.
• Humoral immunity or humoral immunity is the aspect of immunity
that is mediated by macromolecules found in extracellular fluids
such as secreted antibodies, complement proteins, and certain
antimicrobial peptides.
• Humoral immunity is so named because it involves substances
found in the humors, or body fluids.
Platelet or Thrombocytes Physiology
• Platelets/ thrombocytes
• Produced from megakaryocytes
(special cells in the bone marrow).
• Enucleated
• Formation - Bone Marrow
• Died in spleen
• Life span: averagely, 3-5 days in the
blood.
Platelet or Thrombocytes Physiology
• Blood normally contains 1,500,00-4,500,00 platelets mm-3.
• Function: coagulation or clotting of blood, Controlling the
body temp.
• It maintains capillary endothelial cells smooth and integrated
(repairing endothelium and providing nutrition).
• In Dengue platelets decrease.
Coagulation of Blood
Blood Clotting Factors
• Coagulation is the process by
which blood changes from a
liquid to a gel, forming a clot.
• It potentially results in
homeostatis, the cessation of
blood loss from a damaged
vessel, followed by repair.
General mechanism of blood clotting
• Clotting takes place in three essential steps:
1. When there is a trauma to the blood vessel, prothrombin
activator is formed - vessel trauma complex cascade of
chemical reactions takes place in the blood (dozen of
coagulation factors) lead to the formation of a complex of
activated substances collectively called prothrombin activator
2. Prothrombin activator catalyzes the conversion of prothrombin
into thrombin
General mechanism of blood clotting
General mechanism of blood clotting
3. Thrombin converts fibrinogen into fibrin fibers that enmesh
platelets, RBCs and plasma to form the clot.
• Serum : light yellow fluid after blood coagulation.
• Anti clotting factors : Heparin(in blood), calcium oxalate
(responsible for stone formation), Hirudin (found in leech)
Clotting Factors
• They are the proteins in the blood that control bleeding. When a
blood vessel is injured, the walls of the blood vessel contract to
limit the flow of blood to the damaged area. There main function is
to activate the prothrombin activators. There are total 13 clotting
factors:-
1. Factor I - fibrinogen
2. Factor II - prothrombin
3. Factor III - tissue thromboplastin (tissue factor)
4. Factor IV - ionized calcium ( Ca++ )
Clotting Factors
5. Factor V - labile factor or proaccelerin
6. Factor VI - unassigned
7. Factor VII - stable factor or proconvertin
8. Factor VIII - antihemophilic factor (deficiency causes Haemophillia
A)
9. Factor IX - plasma thromboplastin component, Christmas factor
(deficiency causes Haemophillia B)
10. Factor X - Stuart-Prower factor
Clotting Factors
11. Factor XI - plasma thromboplastin antecedent
12. Factor XII - Hageman factor
13. Factor XIII - fibrin-stabilizing factor
• If any of the clotting factors is missing or is not working properly,
the coagulation cascade is blocked. When this happens, the blood
clot does not form and the bleeding continues longer than it
should.
Clotting Factors
• 2 protein : Fibrinogen, Prothrombin
• Vit- Vit K
• Mineral- Calcium
• clot or coagulam formed mainly of a network of threads called fibrins in
which dead and damaged formed elements of blood are trapped.
• Fibrins are formed by the conversion of inactive fibrinogens in the
plasma by the enzyme thrombin.
• Thrombins, in turn are formed from another inactive substance present
in the plasma called prothrombin.
• An enzyme complex, thrombokinase, is required for the above reaction.
Lymph (Tissue Fluid)
• As the blood passes through the capillaries in
tissues, some water along with many small
water soluble substances move out into the
spaces. This fluid released out is called the
interstitial fluid or tissue fluid.
• Exchange of nutrients, gases, etc., between the
blood and the cells always occur through this
fluid.
• Flows in one direction from tissues towards
heart.
• Acts as middleman between blood and tissue.
Lymph (Tissue Fluid)
• Lymph is a colourless fluid containing specialized lymphocytes
which are responsible for the immune responses of the body.
Lymph is also an important carrier for nutrients, hormones, etc.
• Fats are absorbed through lymph in the lacteals present in the
intestinal villi.
• Spleen produces lymph and at the same time it is known as
graveyard of lymph.
Blood Groups
• Discovered by Landsteiner
• Two surface antigens (chemicals that can induce immune
response) on the RBCs namely A and B.
• Similarly, the plasma of different individuals contain two natural
antibodies a and b (proteins produced in response to antigens).
ABO Blood Group System
Inheritance of ABO Blood Group
• Genotype (present in genes, blood group may be dominant and
recessive) and Phenotype (physically appeared):
Question
• What is the blood group of offspring. If the parents have blood group A
and B ?
Solution:
a) A Blood Group
b) B Blood Group
• Genotype:
 AA, AO, BB, BO
• OFFSPRING GENOTYPE:
 AB, OO, AO, BO
• So, the offspring can have the possibility of A, B, O and AB blood group.

Rh grouping
• Another antigen, the Rh antigen similar to one present in Rhesus
monkeys (hence Rh), is also observed on the surface of RBCs of
majority (nearly 80 per cent) of humans.
• Such individuals are called Rh positive (Rh+ve) and those in whom
this antigen is absent are called Rh negative (Rh-ve).
• Blood used in transfusions much match donors for Rh status as well
as for ABO blood group, as Rh- patients will develop anemia if given
Rh+ blood.
• Discovered by Landsteiner and wiener
Rh disease (Erythroblastosis Fetalis)
• Every person has a blood type, (O, A, B, or AB) and an Rh factor,
either positive or negative. The blood type and the Rh factor simply
mean that a person's blood has certain specific characteristics.
• The blood type is found as proteins on red blood cells and in body
fluids. The Rh factor is a protein that is found on the covering of the
red blood cells.
• If the Rh factor protein is present on the cells, the person is Rh
positive. If there is no Rh factor protein, the person is Rh negative.
Rh disease (Erythroblastosis Fetalis)
• Rh factors are genetically determined. A baby may have the blood type
and Rh factor of either parent, or a combination of both parents. Rh
factors follow a common pattern of genetic inheritance. The Rh positive
gene is dominant (stronger) and even when paired with an Rh negative
gene, the positive gene takes over. For example:
 If a person has the genes + +, the Rh factor in the blood will be
positive.
 If a person has the genes + -, the Rh factor will be positive.
 If a person has the genes - -, the Rh factor will be negative.
Rh disease (Erythroblastosis Fetalis)
• When an Rh negative mother has a baby that is Rh positive,
problems can develop if the baby's red blood cells cross to the Rh
negative mother. This usually happens at delivery when the
placenta detaches.
• It may also happen, however, anytime blood cells of the two
circulations mix such as during a miscarriage or abortion, with a fall,
or during an invasive prenatal testing procedure such as an
amniocentesis or chorionic villus sampling.
Rh disease (Erythroblastosis Fetalis)
• The mother's immune system sees the baby's Rh positive red blood
cells as foreign.
• Just as when bacteria invade the body, the immune system
responds by developing antibodies to fight and destroy these
foreign cells.
• The mother's immune system keeps the antibodies in case the
foreign cells appear again, even in a future pregnancy. The mother
is now Rh sensitized.
Blood Transfusion technique by James Blundell
• Circulatory system is essentially a closed container including a
volume of blood equal to approximately 5 litres.
• Principle of transfusion:
 Identification of blood group must be taken before transfusion.
 Cross-match test must be done before transfusion.
 The same types of blood group for transfusion should be firstly
considered.
 O- Negative is universal donor. AB+ Positive is universal recipient.

