Endocrine
System
By Dr Vipan Goyal

ENDOCRINE SYSTEM
• The endocrine system consists of glands that perform very different
functions. They are related to each other because they all secrete
hormones into the blood.
• Organs and glands of the endocrine system secrete hormones to
regulate various body functions.

TYPES OF GLANDS
• Exocrine glands
 Release secretions into duct that carries them to outside of
body. Ex: Sweat glands
• Endocrine glands
 Release hormones directly into bloodstream.
 Have no ducts, referred to as ductless glands
 Example: Thyroid gland
. Mixed glands
 Both endocrine ad exocrine functions. Example : Pancreas
ADRENAL GLANDS
• Two glands, one located
above each kidney.
• Each gland is composed of
two sections :-
1. Adrenal cortex
2. Adrenal medulla
• Adrenal Gland is also called
4S gland i.e. Sugar
Metabolism, Salt retention,
Sex Hormone, Source of
Energy.
Adrenal cortex
• Mineralocorticoid
 Example: Aldosterone
 Regulates sodium and potassium levels.
• Glucocorticoid
 Example: Cortisol
 Regulates Carbohydrates, protein and fats metbolism
• Steroid sex hormones
 Androgens, estrogens and progesterone
 Regulate secondary sexual characteristics
Adrenal medulla
• Present in Inner portion of adrenal.
• Secretes Epinephrine and nor-epinephrine.
• Epinephrine is also called adrenaline. (emergency hormone / 3F
Hormone Fear, Fight and Flight )
• Critical during emergency situations
 Increases blood pressure
 Increases heart rate
 Increases respiration rate
Ovary
• There are two ovaries in a female.
It is located in pelvic cavity of
females. It secretes female sex
hormones,
1. Estrogen
2. Progesterone
• Estrogen is responsible for:-
 Female sexual characteristics
(secondary sexual characters)
 Regulation of menstrual cycle
Ovary
• Progesterone Hormone
 It maintains suitable uterine environment for pregnancy.
 It stimulates the thickening of uterus lining and causes
development of breasts in the later month of pregnancy.
• Relaxin Hormone
 Found in uterus and placenta and widens the uterine cervix so
that a child delivery can take place easily.
Testes
• Two oval glands located in scrotum.
• Leydig cells Secrete male sex hormone, testosterone (produces sperms
and secondary sexual characters to male)
Pancreas
• It is located along curvature of
stomach, only organ that has both
endocrine and exocrine functions.
• Its exocrine portion, releases
digestive enzymes through duct
into duodenum and endocrine
sections of the pancreas contains
islets of langerhans which
produces insulin and glucagon.
Pancreas
• Insulin
 It is produced by beta cells and stimulates cells of body to take
in glucose from bloodstream. It lowers the blood sugar level and
occurs when the body needs less glucose.
• Glucagon
 It is produced by alpha cells and stimulates liver to release
stored glucose into bloodsream. It raises blood sugar levels and
occurs when body needs more glucose
THYROID GLAND
• It is located on either side of trachea
and resembles a butterfly in shape. It is
divided into right and left lobes.
• It controls Basal Metabolic Rate (
minimum energy requirement for
maintenance of body during rest or
sleep)
• For normal human adult it is 1600
kcal/day.
• It produces thyroid hormones:
1. Thyroxine (T4)
2. Triiodothyronine(T3)
THYROID GLAND
• It needs iodine to make hormones. These hormones :
1. Regulate energy production
2. Adjust metabolic rate
• It also secretes calcitonin, regulates level of calcium in bloodstream.
• If calcium levels in blood rise too high:
1. Calcitonin levels in blood increase.
2. Increases deposition of calcium into bone.
3. Lowers levels of calcium in bloodstream.
• Its action is opposite of parathyroid hormone.
PARATHYROID GLANDS
• It is made by four tiny
glands, located on dorsal
surface of thyroid gland.
• It secretes parathyroid
hormone (PTH), which
regulates level of calcium
in bloodstream.
PARATHYROID GLANDS
Hormones released are:
1. Parathyroid Hormone: It is also called Collip’s Hormone.
• If calcium levels in blood fall too low:
 Parathyroid hormone levels in the blood increases.
 Stimulate bone breakdown.
 Regulates more calcium into the blood stream.
• Removal of the gland leads to death due to tetany. (cramps, tremors)
2. Parathyroid hormone works in partnership with calcitonin from the
thyroid gland. The 2 hormones have the opposite effect.
ENDOCRINE GLANDS OF THE BRAIN
• Pineal gland
 The pineal gland is a part of the
thalamus region of the brain.
 It secretes melatonin. It plays a
role in regulating body’s circadian
rhythm-24 hour clock that
governs periods of wakefulness
and sleepiness.
• Pituitary gland
 Smallest and Master gland
 Controlled by Hypothalamus
(thermostat)
ENDOCRINE GLANDS OF THE BRAIN
• Anterior pituitary: It referred to as ‘Master gland’, secretes
hormones that regulate other endocrine glands.
 Thyroid- stimulating hormone (TSH) regulates function of
thyroid gland.
 Adrenocorticotropin hormone (ACTH) regulates function of
adrenal cortex.
 Follicle stimulating hormones (FSH)- It is responsible for
development of ova and sperm and also stimulates ovary to
secrete estrogen.
ENDOCRINE GLANDS OF THE BRAIN
 LH (luteinizing hormones)- It stimulates secretion of sex
hormones and plays a role in releasing ova in females.
 It also secretes growth hormones or somatotropin and
stimulates cells to grow and divide.
 Prolactin (PRL), stimulates milk production in breast.
 Melanocyte-stimulating hormones (MSH), stimulates
melanocytes to produce more melanin.
ENDOCRINE GLANDS OF THE BRAIN
Posterior pituitary
1. Antidiuretic hormones (ADH), also called vasopressin. It promotes
water re-absorption by the kidney tubules.
 Maintains water balance in the body and reduce the volume of urine.
 Hypoactivity leads to Diabetes Inspidus in which patient excrete large
amount of urine.
 Also causes contraction of small arteries causing increase in Blood
Pressure.
2. Oxytocin (OXT), stimulates uterine contractions during labor and
delivery. After birth stimulates release of milk from breast.
Thymus gland
• It is located in mediastinum, part of
immune system and secretes thymosin
hormone.
• It is essential for growth and
development of thymic lymphocytes or T
cells.
• Thymosin hormone is critical part of the
body’s immune system.
• It is present at birth and grows to largest
size during puberty. At puberty begins to
shrink and eventually is replaced with
connective and adipose tissue.
DEFICIENCY DISEASES
Adrenaline hormone
1. Cushing’s syndrome
 The cause of Cushing syndrome is excess cortisol secretion that
doesn't depend on stimulation from ACTH (AdrenoCorticoTropic
Hormone ) and is associated with disorders of the adrenal glands.
2. Addison’s disease
 Addison's disease, also known as primary adrenal insufficiency and
hypocortisolism, is a longterm endocrine disorder in which the adrenal
glands do not produce enough steroid hormones.
 Symptoms generally come on slowly and may include abdominal pain,
weakness, and weight loss.
DIABETES MELLITUS
• Insulin dependent diabetes
mellitus
 Also called type 1
 Develops early in life
 Destruction of islet cells
 Person makes too little
insulin. Does not take insulin
• Non- insulin dependent
diabetes mellitus
 Also called type 2
 Develops later in life
 Person makes enough insulin,
but it has lost ability to
regulate cells.
 Must take insulin injections
Treated by diet, exercise, and
oral medications.
PITUITARY GLANDS
• DISEASES CAUSES
1. Acromegaly Chronic hypersection of growth hormone in
