MUGHAL EMPIRE
Akbar
(1556-1605)
By Dr Vipan Goyal

AKBAR (1556-1605)
• Akbar’s position was in dangerous when he succeeded his father
Humayun as Delhi was seized by the Afghans.
• Jalal ud Din Mohammad Akbar, a name, a legacy in itself, was born
to King Humayun and Begum Hamida Banu, while they were in exile
in the year 1542.
• When Humayun was retreating from Bikaner, he was gallantly
offered shelter and help by the Rana of Amarkot.
AKBAR (1556-1605)
• It was at Amarkot, in 1542, that Akbar, the greatest of the Mughal rulers,
was born.
• He was keenly interested in learning all warfare techniques and was totally
disinterested in reading or writing.
• He was in fact not at all educated yet he had a keen interest in gaining
knowledge about many things.
• At a very small age of just 13 years Jalal, was conferred the title of
Shehanshah Akbar under the keen guidance of Bairam Khan.
• In 1556, Akbar was crowned at Kalanaur at the age of merely thirteen
years and four months.
AKBAR (1556-1605)
• It was in Bairam’s command that Akbar's army defeated Hemu
Vikramaditya in the Second Battle of Panipat in 1556 AD.
• Hemu, the PM of Adil Shah Suri, was defeated. Hemu is considered the
last Hindu King of Delhi. He was 14th and last king who took the title of
Vikramaditya.
• During the first 5 years of Akbar’s reign, Bairam Khan acted as his
regent.
• Later, Akbar removed Bairam Khan and sent him to Mecca but Bairam
Khan was killed by an Afghan ruler Mubarak Khan on his way at Patan,
Gujarat.
AKBAR (1556-1605)
• The period 1560-62 is also referred to as ‘Petticoat Government’s
rule as the nurse of Akbar, Maham Anga (often called Akbar’s foster
mother) attempted to keep Akbar as a puppet ruler after Bairam
Khan’s death. She died in 1562.
• He conquered Malwa in 1561 defeating Baz Bahadur.
• He was later made the Mansabdar to honour his skill as a musician.
• Then defeated Garh-Katanga (ruled by Rani Durgawati) followed by
Chittor and Ranthambore.


Akbar’s Relation with Rajputs
• Akbar followed a policy of reconcillation with the Rajputs. Some of the
Rajput Princes entered into matrimonial alliances with him.
• In 1562, when Akbar was going to Ajmer, Bhara Mal paid personal homage
to Akbar, and cemented the alliance by marrying his younger
daughter, Harkha Bai, to Akbar.
• For four generation, the Rajputs served the Mughals and many served in
the positions of military generals as well.
• Akbar appointed Raja Man Singh and Raja Bhagawan Das in the senior
position of the Mughal Administration.
Akbar’s Relation with Rajputs
• Though majority of the Rajput states surrendered to Akbar, the Ranas of
Mewar continued to confront even though they were defeated several times.
• In 1576, the Mughal Army led by Raja Man Singh and Asaf Khan defeated Rana
Pratap Singh in the battle of Haldighati. Maharana Pratap had to flee the field
on his trusted Chetak.
• Akbar’s policy towards Rajput was combined with a broad religious toleration.
• All these activities paved the way for friendship between Rajputs and Mughals
(except Mewar).
Akbar’s Relation with Rajputs
• He won Gujarat in 1572. It was in order to commemorate his victory of
Gujarat that Akbar got the Buland Darwaza constructed (in 1602) at
Fatehpur Sikri.
• In 1586, he conquered Kashmir and in 1593, he conquered Sindh.
• His last conquest was at the fort of Asirgarh in Deccan. (Fort is key to
Deccan)
• At his death in 1605, his empire included Kashmir, Sindh, Kalandhar and
extended as far as Godavari in the Deccan.
Akbar’s Religious Policy
• Akbar was not an extreme Muslim rather he is known for his tolerance
towards all the religions. This is what made him so famous amongst his
people.
• Akbar made many religious matrimonial alliances through which he sent a
message of unity and togetherness. His marriage to the Rajput princess
Jodha, says volumes about his kindness.
• Akbar got a temple constructed for Jodha in his palace, even though there
was a lot of opposition for the same.
Akbar’s Religious Policy
• He allowed his Hindu wives to worship their own gods.
• He appointed learned Hindu Pundits at important Government posts.
• He talked to general people and heard their woes at DIWAN-E-AAM.
• He interacted with Hindu Muslim and Christian scholars on important
issues in DIWAN-E-KHAAS.
• The policy of religious tolerance known as Sul-i Kul (Peace with all) was
basically aimed at proper functioning of political and administrative
machinery of the Empire.
Akbar’s Religious Policy
• Akbar gave the title of Jagat Guru to Harivijaya Suri and yug pradhan to
JinChandra Suri.
• In 1575, Akbar built Ibadat Khana (House of worship) at his new capital
Fatepur Sikri and invited scholars from all religions like Christianity,
Hinduism, Jainism, and Zoroastrianism. ( like Purshottam Das/ Hindu,
Maharaji Rana/ Parsi, Harivijaya Suri/ Jain, Monserate and Aquaviva/
Christain)
• He did not like the intrusion of the Muslim Ulemas in political matters.
Akbar’s Religious Policy
• Like other Muslim monarchs, Akbar was, at least in theory, subordinate to
the wishes of entire Muslim population (millat), which, in turn, was
guided by the Muslim learned divines called the Ulema.
• Akbar sought to remove this check to his will and became the supreme
authority over his Muslim subjects by promulgating
the Infallibility Decree (Mazhar) in September 1579 and proclaimed title
Sultan-i-Adil.
Akbar’s Religious Policy
• Akbar believed that the king must be absolutely tolerant to every
creed and must establish universal peace in his dominion.
• Akbar abolished the Pilgrimage tax in 1563 and Jizya in 1564 as both
were based on religion discrimination.
• In 1582, he propagated a new religion called Din Ilahi or Divine
Faith.
• Akbar’s so-called Din-i Ilahi was an amalgam of Sufism,
Hinduism and Zoroastrianism.
About Din Ilahi (Tauhid-i-Ilahi)
• Birbal (first and last Hindu), Abul Fazal and Faizi joined the order.
• The new religion believed in one God. It had all the good points of every
religion. Its foundation was balanced.
• It didn’t endorse any philosophy. It aimed at bridging the gap that
separated different religions.
• The new religion had only 15 followers including Birbal.
• Akbar did not compel anyone to join his new religion. However, the new
religion proved to be a failure, after Akbar’s death
Land Revenue Administration
• With the help of Raja Todar Mal, Akbar experimented on the land
revenue administration, which was completed in 1580.
• The land revenue system was called Zabti or Bandobast system or
Dahsala System.
• The revenue was fixed on the average yield of land measured on
the basis of previous ten years.
Land Revenue Administration
• The land was divided into four categories
1. Polaj (cultivated every year)
2. Parauti (once in two years)
3. Chachar (once in three or four years)
4. Banjar (once in five or more years)
• Payment of revenue was made generally in cash.
• Bigha was adopted as standard unit of area ( 60 X 60 yards).
• A new gaz or yard, gaz-i-Ilahi was introduced.
Mansabdari System
• Akbar introduced the Mansabdari system in his administration in 1575.
(borrowed from Persia) to organize the nobility as well as the army.
• Under this system every officer was assigned a rank (Mansab)
• Princes of royal blood received even higher ranks.
• The ranks were divided into two – Zat and Sawar.
• Zat means personal and it fixed the personal status of a person. It was
conferred by a king on mansabdar.
• Sawar rank indicated the number of cavalrymen of a person who was
required to maintain. Every sawar had to maintain at least two horses.
• All appointments, promotions and dismissals were directly made by the
emperor.
Art and Culture
• Besides being a dedicated ruler Akbar was also a great patron for art and culture.
• He enjoyed the company of poets and singers and all types of artistic people.
• His forts and palaces in and around Delhi are great masterpieces of unmatched
workmanship.
• Few amongst those are Fatehpur Sikri, Allahabad Fort, and Agra Fort etc.
• He was also a great lover of music and poetry, his durbar was a unique
amalgamation of great artists, scholars, poet, and singers etc. who kept the aura
happy.
• This love for culture made him collects his “Nine Jewels or Naurattans” who excelled
in their fields of art and knowledge.
Naurattans/ Navratana
Name Work
