MUGHAL EMPIRE
Jahangir
(1605-1627)
By Dr Vipan Goyal
Jahangir (1605-1627)
• In 1605, Prince Salim succeeded with the title
Jahangir (Conqueror of World) after the death of
Akbar.
Birth of Salim
• Prince Salim was born to father Akbar and mother
Harkha Bai due to the blessing of the holy man
Salim Chisti.
• Salim Chisti was one of the descendents of Khwaja
Moinuddin Chisti of Ajmer.
• Akbar named his son Salim with due respect to the
holy saint.
• Akbar called him Sheikhubaba.
• He was the student of Bairam khan’s son AbdurRahim-Khan-i-Khana.
Jahangir (1605-1627)
• He gave his father the terminating shock by killing Abul Fazal in 1602.
• He was of a violent temperament and like his other two despicable
brothers Murad and Daniyal, he was a notorious and drunkard.
• The coin in which he has been engraved with a wine cup in his hand is a
testimony to his habit as a habitual drunkard.
• However, when he ascended the throne, he was a man of 37 years and
had become “mature”.
Jahangir (1605-1627)
• After his coronation, he assumed the title of Nur-ud-din Muhammad
Jahangir Badshah Ghazi.
• He continued to be sober in the day time and introduced famous
regulations such as forbidding sale of wine and even tobacco.
• Jahangir mostly lived in lahore which he adorned with gardens and
buildings.
• He defeated and imprisoned Son Khusrau.
• He also beheaded Guru Arjun, the 5
th Sikh Guru and one of the supporters
of Khusrau.
Jahangir (1605-1627)
• One of his supporters, Guru Arjun, the fifth Sikh Guru, was beheaded.
• Rana Amar Singh (son of Maharana Pratap) of Mewar submitted before
Jahangir in 1615.
• Rana’s son Karan Singh was made a mansabdar in the Mughal court.
• Faced a formidable opponent in Malik Amber in his expedition to
Ahmednagar. This was led by Akbar’s son Khurram but ended in treaty.
• Jahangir also won Kangra.
• His greatest failure was the loss of Kandahar to Persia in 1622.
Nur Jahan
• In 1611, Jahangir married Mehrunnisa who was known as Nur Jahan (Light
of World). She was the widow of Sher Afgani in 1611. The title NurJahan
was conferred on her by Jahangir.
• She had great influence on Jahangir’s life, as she was given the status of
Padshah Begum, coins were struck in her name and all royal farmans
beared her name.
• She got high position for her father Itmad-ud-daulah and her brother Asaf
Khan.
Nur Jahan
• Asaf Khan elder brother of Nur Jahan was appointed as Khan-i-Saman, a
post reserved for the nobles.
• In 1612, Asaf Khan’s daughter, Arjumand Banu Begum (later known as
Mumtaj), married Jahangir’s third son, prince Khurram (later Shah Jahan).
• This alliance practically ruled the empire for 10 years.
• Problems arose whe Nurjahan married her daughter Ladali Begum by Sher
Afgani to Jahangir’s youngest son Shahrayar.
• Now Nurjahan supported him for the heir apparent.
Nur Jahan
• All these events hampered the military events for the recovery of
Kandahar.
• Nur Jahan’s marriage with Jahangir almost eclipsed his personality.
• Jahangir in his biography ‘Tuzuk-i-Jahangir’ himself wrote “I have sold my
kingdom to my beloved queen for a cup of wine and a dish of soup.”
Restoration of Mohammaden Faith
• This son of a philosopher King and a Rajput princess professed himself as a
Muslim and restored the Mohammaden faith and Hijra Chronology (on
coins) his father had abandoned.
• But, like his father, he was tolerant towards Hindus and equally tolerant
towards the Christians. He continued to marry the princesses of the Rajput
aristocrats.
The Justice Bell (Zanzir-i-Adil)
• He was active in redressing the grievance of the people and had a
golden chain and bell attached to the gate of his palace in Agra, so
that all who wished to appeal to him could ring him up.
• However, it is not clear, who was eligible to ring the emperor up.
Painting
• Jahangir’s tenure is called golden age of painting.
• Ustad Mansur and abul Hasan was famous painter.
• Jahangir has given the title of Nadir-ul-Jamat to Abul Hasan and Nadil-ulAsar to Ustad Mansur.
• Jahangir has started painting school ( chitranshala) in Agra under Akarija (
painter of herat)
Important Facts
• In 1622-23 ShahJahan (Khurram) and in 1626 Mahabat Khan mughal
general revolted against Jahangir.
• Mahabat khan kept Jahangir in jail near Jhelum river.
• Nur Jahan played a very important role to suppress the revolt of Mahabat
Khan
• Nurjahan’s mother Asmat Begum known for having invented the famous
rose perfume called Jahangiri-itr, which was described by Jahangir as the
discovery of his reign
Important Facts
• Jahangir also started system of Do Aspa (mansabdar have to kept 2 times
horses) and Singh Aspa (mansabdar have to kept 3 times horses)
• He also laid a number of gardens such as Shalimar and Nishat Gardens in
Kashmir.
• Two visitors namely Captain William Hawkins and Sir Thomas Roe came to
the court of Jahangir. The latter who was the ambassador of King James
