Study of Plants (Botany)
• MESOPHYTES
 Those plants which require moderate supply of water. Ex: corn
• XEROPHYTES
 Those which live in deserts or dry places and can withstand scantly
supply of water. Ex- cactus
• HYDROPHYTES
 Those which thrive in watery or moist places and require abundant
supply of water.
 Ex: Water lilies, Nymphaea Alba, Nelumbo Nucifera, Water Hyacinth
etc
Study of Plants (Botany)
• HALOPHYTES
 Those which live in watery places, but in which the water is
absorbed with difficulty because of its high salt content.
 Eg:- Sea-grasses are found on the seaward edges of lagoons,
Mangroves.
Classification
• Based on their habitat or environment location
 Aquatic plants- live in water
 Terrestrial plants – live on land
 Aerial plants – are above- ground and attached to other
plants. Ex: orchids
Classification
• Based on plants life duration
 Annual plants- live for one year or only one growing season.
Examples: corn, wheat, rice
 Biennial plants – live for two years. The first year is mainly
limited to vegetative growth, and the second year is its
reproductive year, produce flowers in 2nd year. Examples :
onion, carrot
 Perennial plants – Produce seeds year after year. Examples:
fruits like pineapple, strawberry, banana, apple, tomato.
Classification
• Based on plants habit of body appearance
 Trees- woody plants with single main stem which is commonly
about 20 ft in length.
 Shrubs – woody plants in a relatively short. Ex: roses, jasmine
 Herbs – Plants with soft stems. Ex : basil, mint
• * All herbs can be shrubs, but not all shrubs are herbs.
Classification of plants
• Cryptogamae and Phanerogamae
 In 1883, A.W.Eichler gave a system of classification for the
whole plant kingdom.
 Eichler classified the plant kingdom into two sub- kingdoms.
 They are cryptogamae and phanerogamae.
Classification of plants
Classification of plants
• THALLOPHYTA
 Undifferentiated body are called Thallus. They don’t have
vascular system. Ex : algae, lichens
• BRYOPHYTA
 No proper root or shoot system., no vascular system. Ex:
Mosses, liverworts and hornworts.
• PTERIDOPHYTA
 It has differentiated root or shoot system. The vascular system is
present. Ex: Ferns
Classification of plants
• GYMNOSPERMS
 They don’t have flowers, seeds are naked and born on scales of
cones. Ex: Evergreen, cycads
• ANGIOSPERMS
 They have flowering plants, have seeds, contained in a fruit. Ex:
Monocotyledons, Dicotyledons.
Cryptogamae vs. Phanerogamae
Cryptogams Phanerogams
They reproduce by forming spores They reproduce by forming seeds
Their reproductive organs are hidden Their reproductive organs are exposed
They are less evolved plants They are highly evolved plants
Mostly thylophyta, bryophyta and
pteridophyta are cryptogams
All angiosperms and gymnosperms are
phanerogams
Eg. Mosses and ferns etc. Eg. Mango, rose, pine, banyan etc.
CRYPTOGAMME
• The Cryptogamme are flowerless and seedless plants.
• They are simple plants like algae, mosses and ferns which do not
produce flowers, fruits and seeds.
• Cryptogams are considered as lower plants. It contains three main
groups: Thallophyte, Bryophyte and Pteridophyte.
THALLOPHYTA
• largest group of plant kingdom.
• It is commonly not
differentiated into stem, leaves
and roots, and show no distinct
tissue systems. These are
mostly aquatic plants and found
both in fresh and marine water.
• Ex: algae, fungi and lichens
ALGAE
• Algae are chlorophyll bearing thallophytes. They are mostly aquatic
occurring in fresh water and in sea.
• They exhibit autotrophic mode of nutrition. Example: chlorella,
Chlamydomonas, Cladospora, Sargassum, Gelidium, Laminaria.
• They are largest producer of carbohydrates. Some forms are edible
like Ulva (sea lettuce).
• Agar agar extracted from algae gelidium (Red Algae) used as a
