By Dr Vipan Goyal

AGRICULTURE
• Agriculture is a primary economic activity that includes growing
crops, fruits, vegetables, flowers and rearing of livestock.
• Government’s Target is to Double the farmers’ income by 2022-23
• UN-SDG1: End poverty in all forms.
• UN-SDG2: Eliminate global hunger, protect indigenous seed and
crop varieties, doubling agriculture productivity and small farmer
incomes by 2030.
AGRICULTURE
• Sir Arthur Lewis’ Dual Economy Model : Economic development results in
labourers moving away from agriculture to the more productive industrial
sector, & agriculture sector becomes less important part GDP.
• The number of people employed in agriculture is steadily falling down:
55% (2011) to 42% (2018) (World Bank data).
• The share of agriculture in the total GDP is falling down, but not steadily.
Around 15.4 %
• The growth rate of agriculture has been zig zag due to El-Nino led drought
years.
Green Revolution
• Term was given by William Gaud
• Father of GR was Norman Baurlaug.
• Father of GR in India was M S Swaminathan.
• GR came in 3
rd five year plan ( 1966-67)
• Green revolution refers to the large increase in food production
with the help of High Yield Variety.
Green Revolution
• Phase-1: mid 1960s upto mid 1970s → focus on wheat, rice and
more affluent states such as Punjab, Andhra Pradesh and Tamil
Nadu.
• Phase-2: mid-1970s to mid-1980s → HYV seeds were spread to a
larger number of states and fo variety from just wheat and rice.
• Biofortification: is the process by which the nutritional quality of
food crops is increased. E.g. ICAR developed CR Dhan 310- a rice
variety that has higher protein & zinc content than traditional rice.
Genetically modified (GM) crops
• Hybrid seeds are developed by cross-breeding/cross-pollination
with other plants.
• Whereas, Transgenic/Genetically modified seeds are developed by
transferring selected genes from one organism into another.
• E.g. Bacterium Bacillus thuringiensis genes inserted in cotton → Bt.
cotton
• If bollworm pests eat it, they’ll die due to toxin crystals in the Bt
cotton plant.
BLUE REVOLUTION (for Fishes)
• Agro Ministry → Department of Animal Husbandry, Dairying & Fisheries.
• Government gives money for modernization of boats, marketing & cold
storage infrastructure.
• National scheme for welfare of fishermen which gives money for
construction of houses, tube wells for drinking water etc.
• Promote Inland fisheries, aquaculture & pisciculture i.e. raising fish in
artificial tanks/ponds.
• Mariculture = cultivation of marine organisms in their natural environment
in sea upto 12 nautical miles from coast.
Other Revolutions
• WHITE REVOLUTION
 Father of White Revolution is Dr Verghese Kurien
 Agro Ministry → Department of Animal Husbandry, Dairying &
Fisheries.
• “Pink Revolution” for meat and poultry industry, under Ministry of
food processing
• Yellow revolution in oilseed
• Golden for Horticulture
Other Revolutions
• Golden Fibers for Jute
• Silver for Eggs
• Silver Fibers for Cotton
• Black Revolution for Petroleum products.
• Brown Revolution for Leather/Cocoa/Non-Conventional Products.
• Grey Revolution for Fertilizers.
MINIMUM SUPPORT PRICES (MSP)
• Under the State APMC Acts, the first sale of agriculture commodity
can occur at Agricultural Produce Market Committee (APMC)
Mandis only. However, a farmer may not get remunerative prices at
the Mandi due to following reasons:
 1. Bumper production /supply which brings down the market
prices AND / OR
 2. Cartelization / price-fixing by the mandi-merchants.
• So, to protect the farmers, Government of India announces MSP
before each crop sowing season.
MINIMUM SUPPORT PRICES (MSP)
• MSP covers 22 crops (MSP) + 1 sugarcane (FRP) = 23 viz.
• 14 kharif crops : Kharif: grown in summer / monsoon season.
• - paddy, jowar, bajra, maize, ragi, arhar, moong, urad, groundnut-inshell, soyabean, sunflower, sesamum, nigerseed and cotton;
• 6 rabi crops : - Rabi: grown in winter season. - wheat, barley, gram,
masur(lentil), rapeseed/mustard and safflower
• 3 commercial /cash crops : - Jute, copra and Sugarcane.
MINIMUM SUPPORT PRICES (MSP)
• For Sugarcane, mechanism is different: It requires the sugar mill
companies to pay the minimum Fair and Remunerative Price (FRP)
fixed by Govt. (Whereas for other 22, Govt itself procures at MSP)
• Agro Ministry’s Commission for Agricultural Costs and Prices
recommends MSP (& FRP/Fair and Renumerative price) for sugar)
→ Cabinet Committee on Economic Affairs)
• Procurement Price : The price at which govt is ready to buy the crop
from the farmer for buffer stock.
• Procurement Price is always higher than MSP.

